{
  "doc_id": "24082",
  "text": "Even though cortico-cortical interactions contribute a considerable part of the ipsilateral eye input to V1, still most ipsilateral input arrives through the direct thalamocortical pathway [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , raising the interesting question about the function of this dual ipsilateral eye input. Our findings in adult mice and previously published single unit data [CITATION_3] corroborate observations in young rats showing that silencing the ipsilateral LGN with TTX reduced the ipsilateral eye evoked VEP-amplitude in V1 and prolonged its latency thus uncovering an ipsilateral eye input via the callosum [CITATION_4] . However, the results from juvenile rats are difficult to reconcile with other findings in young mice demonstrating a complete block of afferent field EPSPs in V1 after inactivation of the ipsilateral LGN with muscimol, and thus ruling out a contribution of callosally mediated input from the ipsilateral eye [CITATION_5] . It would be interesting to investigate whether a later maturation of callosal ipsilateral eye input in mice could explain the different findings.",
